equation_narrative.headline: Terminal position encoding drives arginine prediction through co-evolutionary signal and late-layer R-specific channels
equation_narrative.story: Position 74 is the penultimate residue of ubiquitin (LVLRL[R]GG), placing it in a highly constrained C-terminal context. Through layers 1-23, the model assembles a representation dominated by 17 co-evolving positions and minimal structural contacts (only 1 within 8Å), with the logit lens fluctuating through various amino acids (S, Y, H, L, A, E, N) as different contextual features accumulate. The representation character remains diffuse until layer 23, when terminal position encoding and co-evolutionary constraints begin to crystallize. At layer 26, arginine emerges as the lead candidate (14.9%), and between layers 27-33, R-specific prediction channels activate decisively: F30:5781 (28.1 proj), F33:7063 (136.7 proj), and MLP neurons N30:1399, N30:4826, N31:3696 all vote strongly for arginine, driving the final probability to 99.05%.

perception_phase.summary: Layers 1-23 are characterized by extensive information gathering from 17 co-evolving positions but minimal structural context (only 1 contact). Early attention heads (L11:H2 with 1.53 proj, L15:H13 with -2.02 proj) read co-evolutionary signal, while the logit lens shows unstable leadership changes among S, Y, H, L, A, E, and N—reflecting the model's assembly of terminal position features rather than amino acid predictions. Features at layer 9 (F9:5728, F9:1281, F9:2619) encode positional context with high projection values (48.5, 44.6, 43.9), while layer 18 features (F18:7108, F18:7145, F18:7377) begin to encode the chemical character of the C-terminal environment. The representation remains chemically ambiguous through L23, with leucine peaking at 15.6% (L10) and serine reaching 21.3% (L14), but these reflect the model encoding 'terminal position with hydrophobic neighbors' rather than committing to specific residues.
perception_phase.context_character: By layer 23, the representation encodes a C-terminal position (penultimate residue before GG motif) with strong co-evolutionary constraints from 17 distant positions, minimal local structural contacts, and a hydrophobic local sequence context (LVLRL). The chemical character is ambiguous—neither strongly hydrophobic nor charged—reflecting the model's uncertainty about what functional role this terminal position serves.
key_information_sources: Co-evolutionary signal: 17 coupled positions drive extensive attention activity (L15:H13 with 0.933 coevol attention, L22:H10 with 0.466 coevol attention)
Structural contacts: Only 1 residue within 8Å—minimal 3D constraint compared to typical buried positions
Terminal position encoding: Features F9:5728 (48.5 proj), F18:7108 (6.88 proj) encode C-terminal context
Local sequence: Hydrophobic run LVLRL creates representation consistent with non-polar residues through L23

decision_phase.summary: The decision crystallizes between layers 26-33. At L26, arginine takes the lead (14.9%) for the first time, driven by attention head L26 activity (+2.69 total delta, +2.32 from attention). Layers 27-29 see MLP suppression of competing candidates (L27 MLP: -3.11 delta, L29 MLP with N29:873 voting -0.77 against R), but layers 30-33 activate decisive R-specific prediction channels: F30:5781 (28.1 proj), F30:9698 (28.0 proj), F33:7063 (136.7 proj), and F33:3229 (99.1 proj). MLP neurons N30:1399 (0.73 proj), N30:4826 (0.71 proj), N31:3696 (0.60 proj), and N32:234 (0.58 proj) all cast strong votes for arginine, driving probability from 4.9% (L23) to 55.99% (L29) to 99.05% (L33).
decision_phase.transition: The L23-25 boundary marks the shift from perception to decision. At L23, the representation is still diffuse (S leads at 20.6%, R at only 4.9%), with features encoding terminal position context. At L24, attention features F24:10103 (7.18 proj) and F24:10033 (7.07 proj) emerge, and by L25-26, the first R-specific prediction features activate. Layer 26 is the critical transition: attention head activity (+2.32 delta) pushes R into the lead, and the representation shifts from 'encoding C-terminal context' to 'predicting arginine for this C-terminal position.'

candidates.narrative: Arginine emerges at layer 26 (14.9%) and dominates layers 30-33 through massive activation of R-specific prediction channels. Feature F33:7063 (136.7 proj) is the strongest single contributor, followed by F33:3229 (99.1 proj) and F33:5795 (94.2 proj). MLP neurons across L30-32 vote decisively: N30:1399 (0.73 proj for R), N30:4826 (0.71 proj, though it prefers C at 0.82), N31:3696 (0.60 proj), and N32:234 (0.58 proj). The final 99.05% confidence reflects the model's recognition that this C-terminal position, with its co-evolutionary constraints and terminal location, requires a charged residue—specifically arginine over lysine.
candidates.key_layers: Emerges L26 (14.9%), accelerates L29-30 (56.0%), peaks L33 (99.05%)
key_evidence: F33:7063 (MLP, 136.7 proj) — dominant R-specific prediction channel
F30:5781 (MLP, 28.1 proj) — early R-specific feature activation
N30:1399 (0.73 proj) — votes R > F > L
N30:4826 (0.71 proj for R) — strong R support despite C preference

candidates.narrative: Leucine peaks at 15.6% at layer 10, reflecting the model's encoding of the hydrophobic local sequence context (LVLRL). The logit lens projects toward L because the representation at this depth is dominated by features reading the hydrophobic neighbors—not because the model predicts leucine. By layer 23, L rises again to 14.08% as the model consolidates local sequence information, but it collapses in the decision phase (7.4% at L29, 0.33% at L33) as R-specific prediction channels override the hydrophobic signal.
candidates.key_layers: Peaks L10 (15.6%), resurges L23 (14.08%), collapses L29+ (0.33% final)
key_evidence: Early peak reflects hydrophobic context encoding, not prediction
Suppressed by MLP neurons N30:2578 (-0.84 proj) and N32:797 (-1.31 proj) in decision phase

candidates.narrative: Lysine is arginine's closest chemical analog (both positive charges) and shows a late surge at layer 29 (16.44%), suggesting the model briefly considers whether this terminal position requires positive charge generally rather than arginine specifically. However, K collapses in the final layers (0.23% at L33) as R-specific features dominate. The co-evolutionary signal and terminal position encoding ultimately favor arginine's specific chemistry over lysine's simpler charge.
key_evidence: Late peak suggests model considers 'positive charge' as category before committing to R
Suppressed by R-specific channels F33:7063, F33:3229 in final layers

candidates.narrative: Serine leads the logit lens through much of the perception phase, peaking at 21.3% at layer 14 and remaining competitive through layer 23 (20.6%). This reflects the model's encoding of terminal position features and polar context, not a prediction of serine. The representation at these layers is consistent with small, polar residues because the model is assembling 'C-terminal position with co-evolutionary constraints'—serine's logit lens prominence is an artifact of this contextual encoding. S collapses in the decision phase as charged residue features activate.
candidates.key_layers: Leads L1-L23 (peaks 21.3% at L14), collapses L24+ (not in top 5 at L33)
key_evidence: Logit lens prominence reflects terminal position encoding, not S prediction
Suppressed by MLP neurons N29:873 (-0.77 proj) and N31:31 (-0.78 proj) voting against S

turning_points.description: The representation shifts from reading immediate hydrophobic neighbors (L peaks at 15.6% at L10) to encoding broader terminal position context (S rises to 21.3% at L14, A reaches 19.5% at L12). Attention heads read co-evolutionary signal (L11:H2 with 1.53 proj, 0.14 coevol attention), while MLP neurons N12:1454 (0.42 proj for R) and N12:3477 (0.22 proj for R) begin to write weak R-supporting features. This is the model assembling 'what kind of position is this' rather than 'what amino acid goes here.'

The perception phase concludes with consolidation of co-evolutionary and terminal position features. Layer 21 shows strong MLP suppression (total -0.87 answer proj, with N21:1940 voting -0.31 against R), but layer 22 reverses this with major MLP support (total +2.40 answer proj, N22:2718 voting 0.64 for R, N22:486 voting 0.44 for R). By L23, the representation encodes 'C-terminal position with charged co-evolutionary constraints' at 4.9% R probability—ready for the decision phase transition.

The decision crystallizes. At L26, attention head activity (+2.32 delta) pushes R into the lead (14.9%) for the first time. Layers 27-29 show competition: MLP neurons suppress R (L27: -3.11 delta, L29: N29:873 voting -0.77), while K surges to 16.44% at L29. But layer 30 activates decisive R-specific channels: F30:5781 (28.1 proj), F30:9698 (28.0 proj), and MLP neurons N30:1399 (0.73 proj), N30:4826 (0.71 proj) drive R from 16.44% (L29, where K led) to 55.99% (L29 for R) to final dominance.

L11:H2 (1.53 proj, 0.14 coevol attn) and L15:H13 (-2.02 proj, 0.933 coevol attn) gather evolutionary signal, while L22:H10 (-2.28 proj, 0.466 coevol attn) consolidates constraints before the decision phase.

deep_dives.label: Terminal position features L9-18
deep_dives.caption: Layer 9 features (F9:5728 at 48.5 proj, F9:1281 at 44.6 proj) encode C-terminal positional context. Layer 18 features (F18:7108 at 6.88 proj, F18:7145 at 6.11 proj) refine this to 'penultimate position before GG motif' with co-evolutionary constraints.

deep_dives.label: MLP decision preparation L22-23
deep_dives.caption: Layer 22 MLP neurons (N22:2718 voting 0.64 for R, N22:486 voting 0.44 for R) write strong R-supporting features, totaling +2.40 answer proj. Layer 23 continues this (+1.13 total) with N23:4996 (0.35 proj) and N23:4796 (0.33 proj), setting up the L26 transition.

deep_dives.label: R-specific prediction channels L30
deep_dives.caption: Layer 30 activates the first major R-specific features: F30:5781 (28.1 proj, MLP), F30:9698 (28.0 proj, attention), F30:9346 (26.6 proj, MLP). These are high-specificity prediction channels that commit to arginine based on the assembled terminal position + co-evolutionary context.

deep_dives.label: MLP final push L30-32
deep_dives.caption: The decisive MLP votes: N30:1399 (0.73 proj for R), N30:4826 (0.71 proj), N31:3696 (0.60 proj), N31:4749 (0.49 proj), N32:234 (0.58 proj). These neurons recognize the terminal position + co-evolutionary constraints and vote overwhelmingly for arginine over all alternatives.

deep_dives.label: Final prediction layer L33
deep_dives.caption: Layer 33 features deliver the final verdict: F33:7063 (136.7 proj, MLP) is the dominant R-specific channel, supported by F33:3229 (99.1 proj), F33:5795 (94.2 proj), F33:1640 (90.4 proj). These ultra-high projection values reflect the model's 99.05% confidence.

equation_narrative.resolution: The model correctly predicts arginine by recognizing position 74's role as the penultimate residue of ubiquitin's C-terminus, constrained by 17 co-evolving positions and requiring a charged residue for proper function. The perception phase (L1-23) assembles this context through extensive co-evolutionary attention and terminal position encoding, while the logit lens fluctuates through various amino acids as different contextual features accumulate. The decision phase (L26-33) activates R-specific prediction channels (F30:5781, F33:7063) and MLP neurons (N30:1399, N31:3696) that recognize arginine's specific chemistry—not just positive charge generally—as the solution to this terminal position's constraints. The 99.05% confidence reflects the model's certainty that this C-terminal context, with its co-evolutionary coupling and minimal structural contacts, uniquely specifies arginine.
